{"text": "Sweet pool is an unforgettable, gut twisting and tragic yaoi body horror visual novel from Nitro+(Chiral), creators of many esteemed BL (and other) vns. Body horror and erotica seem like a match made in hell, first explored in movies (Cronenberg being the most obvious example) and this game is a worthy addition to that tradition. What sets it apart is that it’s yaoi, gay erotica. But make no mistake, this is a female horror through and through.    Anyone familiar enough with yaoi knows it’s primarily written for women and it rarely deals with actual gay issues. It’s an interesting, and very Japanese, phenomenon that provides a safe distance for exploring some more uncomfortable and darker female issues and fantasies. And that’s never been more clear than in this vn. Yaoi goes where otome dares not. To top it all off it has strong omegaverse vibes and that’s another interesting phenomenon originating from Western slash fandom and serving the same purpose. I was actually very surprised to learn that sweet pool precedes the oldest omegaverse fanfic, so it’s clear there’s some fascinating two-way street influencing going on, from Japan to West and vice versa.  So what are these dark female issues this vn explores? Our male protagonist, Youji, is suddenly faced with inexplicable, and in good body horror fashion, unwanted and out of his control changes to his body. At the same time he starts to attract intense and aggressive attention from two (erm three?) of his fellow students. He seems to react especially strongly to their scent. He’s confused, anxious and horrified at this awakening sexual desire always accompanied by lots of blood and throbbing flesh. All that is tightly interwoven with feelings of disgust and shame. Is he going mad? Those two students seem to know exactly what’s going on and he can’t escape their gaze. If you’re familiar with omegaverse you’ll recognize precursors to tropes such as heat, pheromones and animal instincts. But peel another layer and it becomes a metaphor for a girl going through puberty and all that comes with it: ovulation/menstruation, pregnancy, objectification, being a target of lust and r/ape, being reduced to meat and property, and the ultimate horror of being stripped of humanity and treated as an incubator. The distance the male protagonist provides for a female reader is rather thin here as this still hits too close to home.   Now imagine a female protagonist and how more immediate, direct and disturbing this would all be. While reading, I often wondered what male readers would think about this novel regardless of their sexual orientation. I think this is a good story for all men to read if they want insight into darker female themes. Instead of distance, the male protagonist would provide them with much needed immersion. And if it becomes too uncomfortable, there’s one more layer of distance... Supernatural Lovecraftian horror, with lots of blood and throbbing, icky, squishy, formless flesh chunks pulsating like little hearts. (Sweet pool is often compared to Saya no Uta.) The writing, the language used, as well as sound effects are excellent at making this world viscerally submerged into a meat dimension. The lore is very interesting with Lovecraftian themes coloured with a bit of quasi Christian mythology. It isn’t elaborated thoroughly and it’s left sufficiently ambiguous, just enough to tickle your imagination. The novel is after all more interested in themes about biological determinism and free will to be bogged down in convoluted supernatural plot. Those themes are reflected in choices which consist only of colour coded ‘reason’ or ‘instinct’. But this is a dark, cynical world and no combination of choices will lead you to a good end.  There are 6 endings and 3  : Zenya, Makoto and Tetsuo. The game doesn’t have standard routes since Tetsuo is the main/only “love interest” with four endings and Zenya and Makoto are more like wrong turns. Like I said, all endings are either horrifying and deliciously dark or they range from sad to sadder. Tetsuo endings are permeated by themes of predestination and fate dictated by biological determinism which they can’t completely escape even when choosing reason. It’s playing out almost like classical tragedy in the way all the actors are positioned like chess pieces on destiny’s board. One ending is kind of the best outcome for Youji and Tetsuo   Another ending is darkly romantic and a natural conclusion to themes about instinct. I say romantic, but only if you don’t view romance through rose-coloured glasses. When you really strip it down, romance is inherently dark and illusionary, designed to deceive your rational mind so that you’ll succumb to instinct. Because what else than romance will get you to basically   This is probably the ‘best’ ending thematically in the way it marries horror, sex and romance (“Forever”) This vn is great at making you understand every character and feel compassion for them, no matter how despicable their actions might’ve been. It’s another look at them from a more human perspective. Most characters are victims of circumstances they have no control over. That’s another point in the overall theme of predetermination vs freedom. They are all drawn very distinctly: Zenya with an air of bratty playful menace (made alive and striking by an excellent voice actor, Midorikawa Hikaru); Makoto – a cheerful friend, ‘boy next door’ and a glutton; and Tetsuo – a stone-faced, robotic, imposing alpha presence. I think they were going for animal magnetism :/ And I have to mention an instrumental side character, Kitani – a badass mobster, extremely loyal and moral, who also cooks, sews, is Zenya’s nanny and bodyguard. In another story he would be a hero  .  Music is some of the best I’ve heard in visual novels. It’s heavily influenced by Industrial, from more Experimental and Dark Ambient to Industrial Rock. Early Industrial especially was interested in occult, body horror and themes of sex and death (Eros and Thanatos) so it’s a perfect fit for this story. Still, the sound that haunts me is the weeping violin in “Forever”.  In the end I have to say this should be played patched, absolutely. It’s a crime how the censoring butchered the story. The sex scenes (which include r/ape and gore) aren't placed at the end of routes so that they can just be neatly cut. They are integral, part of themes, the point. You can’t tell a body horror story without the body. The patch can be bought at JAST website and as many people already said it results in broken achievements. You can unlock 3 achievements with patched version and all the others skipping through the vanilla version.  Even with this bit of inconvenience it’s absolutely worth it. This novel isn’t considered a classic for nothing. It should be read by everyone regardless of gender and sexual orientation...providing one has a stomach for it :D", "appid": "852910", "steamid": "profiles/76561198291108165", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "37", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1595592000.0}
