{"text": "TL;DR: The most beautiful game I have played in my entire life. Side-scrolling, platformer, action/adventure, metroidvania, yada yada: the usual classification boxes. GAMEPLAY is fast paced, has you slashing insects with a blue lightsaber and grappling to parkour on nice looking blue flowers. The combat is exciting and addicting, the platforming challenging and everchanging, with more than one solution to get to another area, or to gather an interesting item. Some places are apparently impassable, but after struggling just enough to the point of emptying your mind, you find just that skill that you needed to pass it, and OH boy does it feel exciting to go back and discover what you left behind. It took me 30-ish hours to finish the whole thing. The game magically keeps itself interesting  . \"Ori\" does not use the same narrative device to unravel the story. Every moment, something different and exciting happens. The MAGIC of games is for you to solve problems and feel good about it. It has to be easy enough not to tilt, hard enough to be rewarding. Whenever you're close to concealed territory, you start to hear a faint whisper. I mean, think! Something's mysterious about this. Maybe a hidden life cell nearby? This is a very charming device that reminds you that this is a game, and it's lovingly encouraging you to think for yourself. It's very cute. Everything also wobbles in a cute way: platforms, huts etc. All of this is happening while mindblowing soundtracks are tickling my despicable eardrums. The music is alive, because it's mixed together with the story, and now there's a music for Kun, that means the loss of a friend, there's a music for bossfighting that means redemption (or vengeance). I already checked it out on YouTube and favorited it. There are some crazy parallax ♥♥♥♥ with the graphics going on (meaning: they're impeccable) that truly says that the side-scrolling aspect of it is purely for gameplay purposes: the world you're playing in actually looks 3D AF. A bossfight left me out of breath. The antagonist is terrifying, there are clear cues of imminent danger using scary sound that progressively gets louder. This conveys much more fear than the boss actually confronting you head on. It reminded me of Little Nightmares. It's not hard like Blasphemous, but I finished it on normal. The aesthetic experience at its finest. It tickles the senses nicely, there's ice, sand, grass, fire, monkeys, spikes, insects, plants and a lot of lights. This is unlike anything I've ever seen on LIMBO, Machinarium, MapleStory, Mark of the Ninja or Rayman Legends, because I can't describe the graphics technically for I know ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ about game construction, the only way I can try to communicate this is by saying exactly that: it's unprecedented and beautiful. \"Ori and the Will of the Wisps\" is childlike, and in the best of ways. Funny, cute, weird and otherwordly characters speaking unintelligible language (Moki's little voice! The smiley face on the Yeti, one of Ori's parents. Kwolok is huuuuuuge) This allows for absolute UNBRIDLED freedom to convey feelings, this is why it's tremendous. The more I live and consume stories, the more I realize that the human story is a simple one, and all stories are analogous to it, and we can't stray too much away from it - from this primary paradigm -, under penalty of the story not being relatable. There exists some territory, the beings that dwell therein and there is some sort of natural order. Things are good the way they are. If this were to persist, well, we'd have some sort of unfunny, boring universe. There would be no feelings, connections, consequences, responsibilities - no story to tell. Everyone would just prance about in paradise. Now there are small evils, but fundamentally, in this primary paradigm I'm trying to describe, there is one huge overarching evil. Some kind of chaotic presence that's inherently HORRIBLE. I said huge because it has to be the last of the evils. Not some sort of interpersonal drama, but a fiery earthquake that turns whatever is caught in its wake into disgusting demon cockroaches that kill for pleasure. Something like that. An irrational, relentless chaos. There is also a light to fight against the darkness, some sort of secret power that can be used for good. IN SEQUENCE, this chaos perturbs the natural order. Now the paradigm is laid, and the story can happen/be weaved however the creator wishes. Smaller elements can be added, but it's my understanding that these are the very fundamental aspects the story cannot do without. Some will say: but isn't this simply reality itself? But the game reality is better. To play isn't to escape, because the external fictional narrative (book, movie, game) is superior as it only shows the memorable parts, all the clutter and boring parts are done away with. My feelings are at the very edge of my skin, ready to burst. The night falls, I feel a cold breeze from the plutonian shores, I'm alone. Am I going to live forever? Is this story metaphysically true, can it exist in an universe parallel to our own? Maybe not. I'm sad. Life's not enough. But this little Moki is enough, if the truth were to be inside the very souls of artwork, like a portal, if paintings were windows: to stare deep into the transcendental itself. It is breathtaking, the very moment when you see a power hugely above your own, something beautiful, a greatness so bright that transcends your miserable existence as an anxious, small and fragile thinking machine. I felt this when the gate opened. I won't go too much into it because spoilers. I think it deserved GOTY, an oscar and a trip to mars. A true masterpiece.", "appid": "1057090", "steamid": "profiles/76561198009906325", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1599048000.0}
