{"text": "On the surface Dungreed has everything I think a good roguelite has: good amount of different enemy types, plenty of different kinds of weapons/ items and good controls. However, there is one slight minus and a big minus in Dungreed if you ask me. Slight minus is bosses that respawn after each run. This is not the reason I gave this game a thumb down but I feel like it's important to be noticed in the review. It just feels boring to fight the exact same boss at each run. I wish that the creator of this game Team Hooray would have either had three random picked different bosses for each floor or that one boss stays dead forever in the save file. The big minus I'm talking about is level cap. In Dungreed you have five different stat-sections you increase as you level up your character and when you invest five (5), 10 or 20 points to one of these stat-sections you get a special boost like double jump or shield at the start of each new run. It would see logical that the level cap in this game would be at least 100 (20 points to each of five stat-sections) or maybe even 495 (99 points to each of five stat-sections)?The level-cap is 30. When I first reached lvl 30 and didn't seem to gain anymore experience I thought it was a bug but no. Too fast/ small level-cap in roguelite games is something I'm not a fan of at all as I wrote in my Flinthook review. With modding tools I was able to hack beyond this 30-level cap and defeat the game and see the credits. Like Flinthook, this game is good as a roguelike but not as a roguelite. Personally I can't see any good reason for this 30-level cap and end up giving it thumb down.", "appid": "753420", "steamid": "profiles/76561198271105938", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1597147200.0}
