{"text": "Suicide note (It should be a review for game website, which no longer exists, so I decided to put it here anyway. I'm open for offers btw.) If I would say that “the static speaks my name” is ♥♥♥♥ or the masterpiece, it would be as much a review as tssmn is actually a game. Yes, it would intrigue you by the title and then jump right to the point, but then would find itself shallow and without an ability to perform something meaningful. And more importantly, it won’t waste too much of your precious time and would offer some point of view. If a free game takes you 15 minutes to beat it (only because of mine desperate attempts to find any hidden way or/and meaning), how could you criticize it?! So tssmn cares about your wallet and time (which is money, so its care is twice beneficial), but the game can’t offer anything except that and “shocking” thematic.  And this is disappointing because it got tightness in the air, a game like that desperately needs, but catharsis of the story is too weak to sympathize, it just leads you to inevitable. Do you really want to kill yourself only because you found the rope and someone told you so?  Do you really want to play the game only because it’s free and short? Well, maybe you do, how could I know. It might be easily the end of my review, but the journalistic rule says to avoid rhetorical questions at the end of any article, so let’s talk about theme of the game, we got no choice, because other aspects of it are not worth a space on the paper (screen? nevermind), as I mentioned before. So tssmn explores the dark side of human consciousness as well as “Depression Quest” which made a lot of noise some time ago, but it was nothing to do with its theme or quality. DQ reminds some physiological test, while tssmn is more like a manual; it isn’t asking any whys. Sadly both games failed to deliver gameplay-wise mumbling something about the importance of its ideas. You really need to get your thoughts straight before a public debate on such topics, because loud statement couldn’t substitute story, game mechanics and the gameplay itself.  We all know that those things exist, although sometimes afraid to talk about them, would you mind to make an actual game about it? Oh my, the rhetorical question again. So it was inevitable as well.", "appid": "387860", "steamid": "profiles/76561197974517652", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "11", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1447156800.0}
