{"text": "Kickstarter backer here. The devs (go to the forums they even confess about it) developed the game content complete, planning to cut content out, to sell it as DLC. Then they posted as a kickstarter-backer-only info: \"We heard that it is pretty unpopular to cut out content to sell it as DLC. Therefore we disguise this practice with a trick! We will cut out content and sell it half a year later. This way people will think, we developed this content post release! Ain´t we genius?!\" The thread:  Well devs... No. Actually. F#ck you. I posted this kickstarter-only-info in the steam forums public, The devs had no choice to confess, but they STILL sticked to their plan... Therefore up to this point kickstarter backers did not receive the full content of the game, nor did anybody else, altough everything has been developed pre-release and is just held back to disguise how dirty those devs are.", "appid": "324740", "steamid": "profiles/76561198005632686", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "129", "votes_funny": "6", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1499688000.0}
{"text": "Unfortunately just not good. I'm sure the performance issues are something that can easily be addressed further down the line and during Early Access you cant really judge them all too much for it. To me the main issues are something that's fundamentally wrong with the gameplay itself. First of all the characters movement feels much too indirect, making precise movement rather difficult even from a standstill which doesn't help the rather dodgy hit detection on buildings. Another problem is a personal taste, the low time to kill is probably comparable to what the modern Battlefield and Call of Duty games call Hardcore mode. I understand some people enjoy it but to me it feels incredibly counter-intuitive when a fast-paced game tries to add depth by making people die quicker. However, this issue is then countered by suddenly adding game-y aspects of having more armor that then protects you from arbitrary selections of guns, to be honest this just feels like there were two design documents and they only had money for one game so you have this mix and match of arcade and realism that doesn't feel great. In the end the question the developers should have asked themselves is: What makes our game fundamentally different from an already existing game from a company with vastly more money and manpower And the answer is: not enough If you want something very similar to this, buy Battlefield 4. It has more players, content and polish", "appid": "674020", "steamid": "profiles/76561197997854616", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "3", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1561204800.0}
