{"text": "Assassin's Creed Brotherhood, originally released in 2010 for PS3 and X360 and five months later for PC is the fourth main title in the Assassin's Creed series and certainly is one of the favorite of most of fans, but once one take the rose-tinted glasses the game turns out to be a really mediocre experience nowadays.  Let's start analysing the PC port. Basically, it's serviceable. There isn't any FPS cap and it supports ultrawide resolutions without major problems, however, more than enough you will be encountering texture and shadows flickering. The graphical options menu isn't nothing worthy to mention as the options are really simple, no advanced features are present here. It does its job though, runs well and it's optimized for a large amount of configurations, definitely the ultimate version of the game even considering the PS4 / XONE \"remaster\". The game uses uPlay to be launched even on Steam but I didn't had any problems with it, worth to mention tho.  Now into the game itself. The story takes off where AC2 left and we once again are in the control of one of the best characters made by Ubisoft, Ezio Auditore. After completing his quest on AC2, Ezio goes back to his uncle's villa to commemorate his victory but his vacation is interrupted by some unfriendly faces from AC2. Now he is again on a quest for revenge as well to close off things with his main enemies from now on, the Borgia family.  While the Ezio's development is interesting, the way that the story does really isn't. Most likeable characters from AC2 are gone in this game and the remaining ones are mediocre-written at best. Honestly, there's some scenes that once described you could think that is from one of the 90's cartoons for kids. More importantly to be honest - Leonardo, one of the most interesting characters on AC2 has a minimal presence where he's only used as a way to upgrade your equipment. The setting of ACBH is dull, at least a big part of it. Unlike AC2 that features multiple regions, ACBH is limited to Rome. Not the full-of-life and blooming Rome that we always think of, but a poor, sad Rome where other than its \"center\", it's pretty much just ugly to be honest. Compared to Venice it really doesn't hold a candle.  The story itself is not great. Again, you start where AC2 left and now looking for revenge on the Borgias. There's a mini betrayal-plot where one of your friends suspect of another one. Is almost comical the way it develops and once you reach the last mission in the game, it seems that there was a giant timeskip as you're thrown in a different map to finish off your quest. It seems rushed as Ubisoft was too tired to write the remaining of the story and just said \"frick it\". The story and location doesn't kill Brotherhood however, it's the mission design that does. If there's one game that does justice for the AC fame of \"tailing simulator\", this is Brotherhood. There's an unhealthy amount of tailing missions that are really bad designed. The character has an obvious path that is stated in the dialogue but you still need to tail him, let him distance enough from you vision and you have to try it again. Don't act like the game wants you to do, even if you just want to kill in a different way or just go for another opening in a area, you will be somehow detected. I still have nightmare with the mission where you have to infiltrate a French camp because unless you do exactly like the game wants, it's going to restart from the last checkpoint. It's pretty much GTA 3 all again where the open-world design collides with the extremely linear mission structure and make to a really unpleasant and bad aged experience. Not everything from Brotherhood is bad of course. The soundtrack reuses some of the AC2 songs but there isn't a problem with this at all, Jesper Kyd still is one of the best when it comes to music in gaming and it's no different in BH. The multiplayer mode, while hard to find opponents nowadays, expect a blast when you find players. And the gameplay mechanics, especially the combat ones are still great.  Can't forget to mention the new \"Brotherhood system\" - you are able to recruit Assassins that can be used to bring income from doing missions or directly help you in battles. The game really give focus to this mechanic, even enforcing it sometimes but it works! It's really cool to call your Assassins in big battles, something I missed from the original AC2. To get Assassins slots you will need to \"burn down\" templar towers, which can be fun or stressing as some of them will fight, others will runaway, in rare occasions which I unfortunately experienced once they will bug and just get killed as soon as they spawn making the whole thing riskless - that only happened twice though.  Another new mechanic is the \"Rome restoration\". Ezio is able to purchase and invest on buildings that sells armors, weapons, medicines, poisons, paintings, clothing and bigger pockets so he can carry more ammo, those shops gives you income and so do historic buildings that don't sell anything but gives back a lot of income, that is deposited every 20 minutes you spend roaming in the city or doing missions. Initially it seems cool but at some point you will notice that it really isn't rewarding or anything. Yeah you get discounts but once you reach a point it is going to be meaningless. The game really doesn't hold you once you finish the story and it really doesn't make you want search for collectables or anything.  Overall, AC Brotherhood is the weakest link in the Ezio trilogy and a skippable game if you aren't looking to stress over badly made tailing missions as Revelations has a brief sum up of what happened in the previous titles (AC2, BH). If you want to fully experience the Ezio story, then it may be a necessary game to fully understand Ezio's journey, again, it is an outdated and frustrating game, but surely there's worst options in the market. If we ever get the \"More or Less\" option in the Steam review system I would check ACBH with that option, but since there isn't, then it's a no-no for me. AC2 and AC Revelations got your AC and Ezio needs covered and with those you won't have half of the frustration that you will with Brotherhood.  6.0 / 10", "appid": "48190", "steamid": "profiles/76561198140961454", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "25", "votes_funny": "3", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1529668800.0}
